## 8. Scaling Strategy — Final Design

```
Document Routing:
─────────────────
Hash(doc_id) % num_servers → Consistent server assignment
Benefit: All users of a document hit same server
         No cross-server coordination for normal ops

Hot Document Handling:
──────────────────────
If a document has > N concurrent users:
→ Promote to dedicated server instance
→ Use Redis Pub/Sub for any cross-instance needs
→ Alert ops team for manual scaling if needed

Horizontal Scaling Triggers:
─────────────────────────────
Scale OUT when:  avg CPU > 70% OR ws_connections > 80% capacity
Scale IN when:   avg CPU < 30% AND ws_connections < 40% capacity
Use:             Kubernetes HPA with custom metrics

Geographic Distribution:
─────────────────────────
Region 1 (US):    Primary write region
Region 2 (EU):    Read replica + local WebSocket servers
Region 3 (APAC):  Read replica + local WebSocket servers

Users connect to nearest WebSocket server.
Writes route to primary region.
Reads served locally after initial sync.
Acceptable trade-off: ~50-100ms extra latency for writes
vs. significant latency reduction for reads/presence.
```

